00:04:18.105 --> 00:04:20.084
The fundamental principle of counting.

00:04:20.415 --> 00:04:21.644
This has two parts.

00:04:21.915 --> 00:04:26.655
The multiplication principle says if one
thing can be done in M ways and another

00:04:26.655 --> 00:04:31.575
independent thing in N ways, then both
can be done together in M times N ways.

00:04:31.955 --> 00:04:36.425
The addition principle says if one
event can happen in Nway and another

00:04:36.485 --> 00:04:40.535
in Nway, but they can't happen at
the same time, then either one or

00:04:40.535 --> 00:04:42.425
the other can happen in m plus.

00:04:42.425 --> 00:04:42.515
Nway.

00:04:43.395 --> 00:04:46.665
When the problem screams, order
is important, you can directly

00:04:46.665 --> 00:04:48.195
use the permutation formula.

00:04:48.435 --> 00:04:51.285
Just identify your n
and r and plug them in.

00:04:51.645 --> 00:04:54.825
Similarly, when the order of
selection is not a big deal,

00:04:54.975 --> 00:04:56.505
use the combination formula.

00:04:56.745 --> 00:04:59.325
Just identify your n and r and solve.

00:04:59.745 --> 00:05:03.885
Finally, for those tricky conditional
problems, we have special tactics.

00:05:04.180 --> 00:05:08.055
If certain items must always be
together, just bundle them up

00:05:08.055 --> 00:05:09.675
and treat them as a single unit.

00:05:10.094 --> 00:05:14.414
If certain items must never be together,
find the total arrangements without

00:05:14.414 --> 00:05:18.075
any rules, and then subtract the
arrangements where they are together.

00:05:18.465 --> 00:05:23.445
And if an item has a specific reserved
position, just place it there first and

00:05:23.445 --> 00:05:24.715
then worry about arranging the rest.

