00:08:05.010 --> 00:08:10.380
Example, one permutation question,
how many different four digit numbers

00:08:10.560 --> 00:08:12.539
can be formed using the digits?

00:08:12.539 --> 00:08:17.880
1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6. If no digit is repeated.

00:08:18.284 --> 00:08:25.155
Options, A one 20 B 360
C seven 20 D four 80.

00:08:25.544 --> 00:08:28.365
Understand the question
before moving to explanation.

00:08:28.755 --> 00:08:29.265
All right.

00:08:29.445 --> 00:08:34.574
For the solution first, we need to form
a four digit number from six distinct

00:08:34.574 --> 00:08:39.855
digits without repetition, since 1,
2, 3, 4 is a different number from 4,

00:08:39.855 --> 00:08:42.375
3, 2, 1, the order clearly matters.

00:08:42.780 --> 00:08:45.000
This is a classic permutation problem.

00:08:45.420 --> 00:08:48.660
Our total number of
available digits N is six.

00:08:49.020 --> 00:08:53.910
The number of digits we need to
arrange R is four, so we apply the

00:08:53.910 --> 00:08:57.180
formula PNR, which is B six four.

00:08:57.540 --> 00:09:02.790
This equals six factorial divided
by six minus four factorial, which

00:09:02.790 --> 00:09:05.250
is six factorial over two factorial.

00:09:05.665 --> 00:09:10.945
Calculating this, we get seven 20
divided by two, which gives us 360.

00:09:11.305 --> 00:09:13.675
The correct answer is B 360.

00:09:14.215 --> 00:09:17.065
Example two combination question.

00:09:17.425 --> 00:09:20.725
A committee of three members
is to be formed from a group

00:09:20.725 --> 00:09:22.615
of five men and four women.

00:09:23.065 --> 00:09:27.290
In how many ways can the committee
be formed, if it must consist of

00:09:27.320 --> 00:09:29.455
exactly two men and one woman?

00:09:29.885 --> 00:09:30.545
Options.

00:09:30.814 --> 00:09:35.645
A 20 B 30 C 40 D 50.

00:09:36.035 --> 00:09:38.735
Understand the question
before moving to explanation.

00:09:39.095 --> 00:09:40.324
Let's break this down.

00:09:40.655 --> 00:09:44.915
We are forming a committee, so the
order of selection does not matter.

00:09:45.185 --> 00:09:46.655
It's a combination problem.

00:09:47.074 --> 00:09:51.485
The condition is that we need
exactly two men and one woman.

00:09:51.905 --> 00:09:53.939
So first, let's select the men.

00:09:54.574 --> 00:09:56.824
We need to choose two men from five.

00:09:57.035 --> 00:09:58.595
This is C five two.

00:09:58.954 --> 00:10:00.845
The formula gives us 10 ways.

00:10:01.235 --> 00:10:02.975
Next, we select the woman.

00:10:03.334 --> 00:10:05.495
We need to choose one woman from four.

00:10:05.765 --> 00:10:08.765
This is C four one,
which gives us four ways.

00:10:09.215 --> 00:10:13.715
Since the committee needs men and women,
we use the multiplication principle.

00:10:13.985 --> 00:10:17.795
We multiply the ways to select
men by the ways to select women.

00:10:18.005 --> 00:10:20.615
So 10 times four equals 40.

00:10:20.944 --> 00:10:22.895
The correct answer is C 40.

00:10:23.515 --> 00:10:27.235
Example three permutation
with restriction question.

00:10:27.564 --> 00:10:31.824
In how many ways can the letters of
the word banking be arranged such

00:10:31.824 --> 00:10:34.135
that the two ends are always together?

00:10:34.525 --> 00:10:42.535
Options A seven 20 B 360 C one 20
D two 40 understand the question

00:10:42.535 --> 00:10:43.839
before moving to explanation.

00:10:44.505 --> 00:10:44.925
Okay.

00:10:45.074 --> 00:10:49.485
For our final example, we're arranging
the letters of banking, which has

00:10:49.485 --> 00:10:52.064
seven letters with two identical ends.

00:10:52.545 --> 00:10:56.145
The restriction is that the
two ends must always together.

00:10:56.595 --> 00:11:01.305
The trick here is to treat the items
that must stay together as a single unit.

00:11:01.605 --> 00:11:04.275
So let's bundle NNN into one block.

00:11:04.665 --> 00:11:06.314
Now what are we arranging?

00:11:06.675 --> 00:11:15.015
We have B-A-K-I-G and our new block, nnn,
that makes six effective items to arrange.

00:11:15.435 --> 00:11:19.185
The number of ways to arrange
these six distinct items is six

00:11:19.185 --> 00:11:21.435
factorial, which is seven 20.

00:11:21.885 --> 00:11:25.275
Now we must consider the
arrangements inside our block.

00:11:25.635 --> 00:11:26.810
The block is NN.

00:11:27.340 --> 00:11:31.420
Since both letters are identical,
there is only one way to arrange them.

00:11:31.690 --> 00:11:33.280
NN is just NN.

00:11:33.670 --> 00:11:39.460
So the final calculation is seven 20
multiplied by one, which is seven 20.

00:11:39.760 --> 00:11:42.190
The correct answer is a seven 20.

